, not that I've noticed. Have you had any night sweats? No. And how has your weight been over the last several months? Have you had any weight loss or gain? No, it's been pretty stable. Okay. And have you had any abdominal pain? No. Any diarrhea? No. Or any urinary problems? No. Okay. And in the past, oh, sorry, before that, have you had any nausea or vomiting? No. Okay. And any confusion or changes to memory? No. Okay. Or loss of taste or sense of smell? No. Okay. So you've been experiencing this cough that's been getting worse over the last couple of days, as well as bringing up some yellow sputum and been short of breath. Have you been experiencing any other symptoms? No, that's pretty much it. Okay. And in the past, have you been diagnosed with any medical conditions? I have diabetes, I have high blood pressure, and I have high cholesterol. I see. All right. And do you take medications for those things? Yes. So I'm on Ramiprol for the high blood pressure, Rostostatin for the cholesterol, and insulin for the diabetes. Okay, thank you. And you mentioned you had a similar episode in the past. Were you diagnosed with COPD before? I was. I was diagnosed with COPD about five years back. Okay. Did you have pulmonary function tests for this test where you had to breathe into a tube? Yeah I had that done like five years ago Okay All right Just wanted to see if it was formally diagnosed Sometimes people that important to have those tests done And do you have any allergies? No, none. Yeah. Okay. Okay. And are your immunizations up to date? Yes, I believe so. Okay. And have you had any surgeries or hospitalizations? I had my gallbladder removed when I was in my 50s. and I had a hip fracture three years ago. Okay. And how is your mobility now? Pretty good. My hips still give me some issues once in a while, but for the most part, it's been okay. Okay, that's good. It sounds like the rehab went well. Yeah. And right now, can you tell me a little bit about your living situation, like where you're living and who you're living with? I live by myself in an apartment on the first floor. Okay. And do you smoke cigarettes? No, I quit two years ago. Okay. And that's great. That's great. Prior to that, how long did you smoke for and how much? Oh, for like 40 plus years. I used to smoke a pack a day. Okay. Well, that's great that you quit. So congratulations. Thank you. And do you drink alcohol? I drink once in a while. Like maybe every other day I'll have a glass of wine. Okay. Okay, and anybody, or sorry, have you been around anybody who's been sick recently? I don't know. Or you said that you went to the stores and stuff like that. Yeah, maybe from there, yeah. Okay, and have you traveled anywhere else outside of the city? Not recently, no. All right. um, and any exposures to any like dusts, chemicals, um, things like that. Um, I live in an old building, so maybe, um, but it hasn't bugged me before. Okay. Um, and, uh are you working currently or or retired I retired Okay What did you do before I used to work on the assembly line for Chrysler Okay. Were there any exposures there that you were aware of, like things that you were breathing in? uh not that i was aware of but there were always like smoke and fumes and things like that because it was like a factory so maybe right okay that makes sense um and in the family are there anybody who who's had um problems with their hearts or lungs um my mom had lung cancer when she was 50 and like all the like diabetes, hypertension and high cholesterol runs on my, ran on my father's side of the family. I see. Did anybody have a heart attack or stroke? Yeah, so my father had a heart attack when he was 49. Stroke, I'm not too sure about. Okay, thank you. And so that was all I wanted to ask about. Was there anything else that you wanted to add that I maybe forgot? No, that's about it. But how can I treat myself now? How do I make this cough go away? For sure. So we will first get your vitals here and we'll see if your oxygen levels are low, that it will be important to put on some oxygen first just to make sure that that's stable. And from there, we will get a chest x-ray and run some lab work to try to help figure out the diagnosis better. But in the meantime, we'll use some inhalers because it's possible that this is a COPD exacerbation, similar to last year. And the inhalers should help open up the airways and dilate so it'll make breathing easier. And then also, if it is a COPD exacerbation, it will likely require antibiotics as well, as some steroids for the inflammation for five days. But since your symptoms currently overlap with COVID as well, we'll have to get a COVID nasal swab. Okay. Okay, for sure. Okay. So we'll get that started. Okay. Thank you so much.",0.17137096774193547,0.17011340893929286,0.19065311074850422,11,214,30,1244
